'''Nando Zen Pijnaker''' ({{IPA|nl|ˈnɑndo zɛn ˈpɛi̯.nɑ.kər|lang}};<ref>https://www.instagram.com/reel/DO7XCmGCfrr/?igsh=MWkzYWk3ZmFjd2NpYw==</ref> born 25 February 1999) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre back]] for [[A-League Men]] club [[Auckland FC]]. Born in the [[Netherlands]], he represents the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

== Early life ==
Pijnaker was born in the [[Netherlands]] and migrated to New Zealand with his family at the age of three, settling in [[Rotorua]]. He attended and played football for [[Western Heights High School]]<ref name="RotoruaDaily">{{cite news |last1=Beck |first1=David |title=Former Rotorua footballer Nando Pijnaker signs professional contract |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/rotorua-daily-post/news/former-rotorua-footballer-nando-pijnaker-signs-professional-contract/THUPYCPUTNUXUU3XVU46IDHOQU/ |url-access=subscription |accessdate=11 October 2020 |publisher=[[The New Zealand Herald|NZ Herald]] |date=4 February 2020 |language=en-NZ}}</ref> and also began playing for local club [[Ngongotaha AFC|Ngongotaha]], making his first-team debut at the age of 15.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/|title=Football: Rising star wins place at top academy|date=25 February 2015|via=www.nzherald.co.nz}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Western Suburbs===
In 2015 Pijnaker moved to Wellington to join the [[Olé Football Academy]],<ref name="RotoruaDaily" /> then run by [[Declan Edge]], and played for affiliated club [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs]] in the [[Central Premier League|Central League]] that features teams from the lower half of the [[North Island]] of New Zealand.<ref name="background">{{cite news |last1=Hyslop |first1=Liam |title=Moulding a Kiwi Messi: Ole Football Academy's neverending football quest |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/106870068/moulding-a-kiwi-messi-ole-football-academys-neverending-football-quest |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=21 September 2018}}</ref> Pijnaker was part of the team to win the [[Central Premier League#Past Champions|Central League]] in 2017 and reach the final of the [[2018 Chatham Cup#Final|2018 Chatham Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hyslop |first1=Liam |title=Western Suburbs win Central League title with two games to go |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/95260902/western-suburbs-win-central-league-title-with-two-games-to-go |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=30 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Western Suburbs |url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1532.htm |website=Ultimatenzsoccer |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref name="background"/>

===Eastern Suburbs===
Through the Olé Academy partnership, Pijnaker signed for Olé affiliate [[Eastern Suburbs AFC|Eastern Suburbs]], winning the [[2018–19 New Zealand Football Championship|ISPS Handa Premiership]] and qualifying for the [[2019–20 OFC Champions League|OFC Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Eastern Suburbs' national league win a showcase for youth development |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/111691756/eastern-suburbs-national-league-win-a-showcase-for-youth-development |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=1 April 2019}}</ref>

===Torslanda IK===
Following the conclusion of New Zealand's [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] campaign, Pijnaker joined his former coach [[Declan Edge]] at Swedish [[Division 2 (Swedish football)|Division 2 Norra Götaland]] side [[Torslanda IK]],<ref name="RotoruaDaily" /> a club run in partnership with the Olé Academy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://olefootballacademy.co.nz/the-torslanda-project-the-gothenburg-post/|title=The Torslanda Project - The Gothenburg Post|date=20 August 2019|website=Olé Football Academy}}</ref> He made his debut on 15 June 2019, starting in a 3–2 loss to [[Stenungsunds IF]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stenungsund vs. Torslanda - 15 June 2019 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2019/06/15/sweden/division-2/stenungsund/torslanda-ik/2963088/ |website=Soccerway |accessdate=11 October 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Flying Kiwis – June 18 |url=http://theniche-cache.com/football/2019/6/18/flying-kiwis-june-18 |website=The Niche Cache |date=13 June 2019 |accessdate=11 October 2020}}</ref>

===Grasshopper===
After a 10 day trial, Pijnaker signed in January 2020 with [[Swiss Challenge League]] club [[Grasshopper Club Zürich|Grasshopper]], joining international teammate [[Max Mata]]. He made two appearances for the club.<ref name="Rio">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Tony |title=All Whites defender Nando Pijnaker signs for Portuguese premier league club |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/world-game/122608427/all-whites-defender-nando-pijnaker-signs-for-portuguese-premier-league-club |accessdate=11 October 2020 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=30 August 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|number=1222192508089839616|user=ElemenTwelve|title=🇳🇿 Nando Pijnaker joins...|date=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref name="RotoruaDaily" />

===Rio Ave===
After the short stint at Grasshoper, Pijnaker signed a four-year deal with Portuguese [[Primeira Liga]] club [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]] on 30 August 2020.<ref name="Rio" /> On 31 August 2021, Pijnaker was loaned out to [[Danish 1st Division]] club [[FC Helsingør]] for the rest of 2021.<ref>[https://fchelsingor.dk/2021/08/31/fc-helsingoer-tilfoejer-new-zealandsk-landsholdsspiller-nando-pijnaker-paa-laan-fra-portugisiske-rio-ave-fc/ FC HELSINGØR LEJER DEN NEWZEALANDSKE LANDSHOLDSSPILLER NANDO PIJNAKER HOS PORTUGISISKE RIO AVE FC], fchelsingor.dk, 31 August 2021</ref>

===Sligo Rovers===
On 8 February 2022, Pijnaker joined [[League of Ireland Premier Division]] side [[Sligo Rovers F.C.|Sligo Rovers]] on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sligorovers.com/pijnaker-joins-rovers-on-loan-from-rio-ave/ |title=Pijnaker joins Rovers on loan from Rio Ave |publisher=Sligo Rovers FC |date=8 February 2022 |accessdate=8 February 2022}}</ref> On 21 December 2022, his transfer was made permanent.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sligo Rovers F.C.|url=https://www.sligorovers.com/rovers-complete-transfer-of-nando-pijnaker/|title=Rovers complete transfer of Nando Pijnaker|date=21 December 2022|access-date=15 February 2023}}</ref> On 1 April 2024, Pijnaker suffered broken ribs in a collision with his own goalkeeper [[Edward McGinty|Ed McGinty]] in a 3–0 loss away to [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.ie/regionals/sligo/sport/soccer/sligo-rovers-confirm-nando-pijnaker-has-sustained-broken-ribs/a380595928.html | title=Sligo Rovers confirm Nando Pijnaker has sustained broken ribs | date=5 April 2024 }}</ref> On 1 September 2024, it was announced that Pijnaker had left the club to return closer to home.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2024/0901/1467808-sligo-rovers-confirm-sale-of-defender-pijnaker/ |title="Sligo Rovers confirm sale of New Zealand international defender Nando Pijnaker" |date=September 2024 |accessdate=2024-09-03 |publisher=RTÉ Sport}}</ref>

===Auckland FC===
On 3 September 2024, Pijnaker joined the newly formed [[A-League|A-League Men]] side, [[Auckland FC]], becoming their 22nd signing ahead of their inaugural season in the [[A-League Men]].<ref>
{{cite news |title="All Whites Defender Nando Pijanker[sic] to Join Auckland FC" |url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/all-whites-defender-nando-pijanker-to-join-auckland-fc/ |publisher=Auckland FC |accessdate=2024-09-03 }}</ref>

Pijnaker scored his first goal for the club against [[Sydney FC]], netting the match-winner in the 97th minute. The match-worn shirt from the game was later donated to the [[Auckland War Memorial Museum|Auckland Museum]], where it became part of the museum’s collection representing Auckland FC’s inaugural [[A-League Men]] season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/back-heeled-into-history-iconic-afc-shirt-finds-a-home-at-auckland-museum/ |title=Back-heeled into history: Iconic AFC shirt finds a home at Auckland Museum |website=Auckland FC |date=10 February 2025 |access-date=12 November 2025}}</ref>

==International career==

===U-20===
Pijnaker was named in the [[New Zealand national under-20 football team|New Zealand U-20]] side for the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]]. Pijnaker played in all four games, playing full 90 minutes in all but one of them.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Progress made as Fifa Under-20 World Cup campaign ends with heartbreak, not history |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/113201244/progress-made-as-fifa-under20-world-cup-campaign-ends-with-heartbreak-not-history |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=3 Jun 2019}}</ref>

===National team===
Pijnaker made his senior debut for [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] on 18 November 2019, coming on as a substitute in their 0–1 loss to [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Second-string All Whites fail to seize opportunities in loss to Lithuania |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/117073764/secondstring-all-whites-fail-to-seize-opportunities-in-loss-to-lithuania |accessdate=18 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref>

On 25 June 2021, Pijnaker was called up to the New Zealand squad for the delayed [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| title= Squads named for Tokyo 2020| date= 25 June 2021| publisher= [[New Zealand Football]]| language= en| access-date= 25 June 2021| archive-date= 25 June 2021| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210625021412/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| url-status= dead}}</ref>

On 14 May 2026, Pijnaker was named in the 26-man New Zealand squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=New Zealand Squad Named for FIFA World Cup 2026 |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/nzfootball |access-date=2026-05-17 |website=www.nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Powell |first=Alex |title=Wood, Smith make history as All Whites name 26-man World Cup squad |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/football-world-cup/fifa-world-cup-live-updates-all-whites-name-squad-for-2026-tournament/VO65EA66YRHJTDPOMT4V2RYVZ4/ |access-date=2026-05-17 |website=NZ Herald |language=en-NZ}}</ref>

